John Edward: Language skills are essential for world citizens
Scotland’s independent schools continue to be distinguished by academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with further outstanding exam results and is only underpinned by individual and joint successes in the areas of sport, art, music and other community ventures.
With more than 30,000 students from all over Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to care for their students and their parents at the highest possible level.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further education and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as world citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and sought after in schools as electives.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to someone in a language they understand, you reach their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.”
This is an impressive reminder that we can’t rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s exam results show that languages with the highest enrollment rates are at the top of the rankings of independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who learned foreign languages scored A on the higher exams.
The data collected by 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students in Mandarin achieved the grade A on the higher exams, while 72 percent of students who learned German, 69 percent of students who learned French, and 63 percent of students who also learned Spanish.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now regarded as elective subjects as well as STEM subjects (Natural Sciences, Engineering, Engineering and Mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
According to a 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills, 17 percent of the reasons employers cited for the problems of occupying open positions were related to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary when it comes to preparing young people for their future profession.
As more and more open positions require languages, this knowledge is essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen profession, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage in the future through such a lifelong ability.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give multilingual people an advantage over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage (15 percent).
For this reason, it is important for today’s children that we now invest in language teaching.
Children who speak multiple languages, especially languages of developing countries, will have better chances of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, different languages are taught in all schools.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will be taught languages that are most important for the UK with a view to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Wherever your child’s interests lie, independent schools will always have a number of languages with appropriately specialized teachers to choose from.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary for their success, no matter what the future looks like.
At this point in a global economic environment, it is impossible to deny that languages are still of elementary importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should actually be seen as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
We have to do it.
John Edward is head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
