North Korea Rejects Unilateral Disarmament Without Confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions would deepen its mistrust of the United States and that the country would not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s annual general assembly that North Korea had taken “substantial measures of goodwill” last year, for example, stopping nuclear and missile tests to demolish the nuclear test site and committing to not proliferating nuclear weapons and technologies.
“But we do not see a corresponding reaction from the United States,” he said.
Without trust in the United States, there is no trust in our national security, and under these circumstances, we will by no means unilaterally disarm ourselves first.
While Ri trusted North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded for successive steps, his statement seemed significant insofar as it had not received unilateral denuclearization from the past as it had refused.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a serving US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, in which Kim assured to work towards “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” while Trump pledged North Korea’s security guarantees.
North Korea is pursuing an official end to the 1950-1953 Korean War, while the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington is opposed to demands for an easing of strict international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal by coercion, and is even against the 'declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
“The assumption that sanctions can force us to kneel is a brainstorming of people who don’t know anything about us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not agree on plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. head of state had highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean head of state Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea were the other party on the issue of denuclearization instead of the United States, it would not have come to this standstill in the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula.”
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech differed enormously from his speech last year when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target the US mainland with North Korea’s missiles after “evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, overwhelmed Kim with praise at the United Nations for his courage in taking steps toward disarmament, but he said there was still a lot of work to be done and the sanctions would have to remain in place until North Korea’s denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for it: “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months – it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “enforcement of the Security Council sanctions must definitely continue vigorously until we achieve complete, final and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously stepped up sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in order to financially drain Pyongyang’s nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
