North Korea vowed to demolish a moon, missile base and nuclear complex at a meeting this month if the United States took "corresponding action."
He said Kim had told him that the “appropriate measures” sought were security guarantees given by Trump in Singapore, as well as steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Learn to Sleep Enough in a Course
A new course at Harvard University ensures that all undergraduate students get more sleep this year, a measure against the expanding macho culture of staying awake with caffeine and learning all night long.
One scholar has found that students at the world’s leading university are often unnecessary when it comes to paying attention to themselves.
The course was conceived by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, and is in his opinion the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to bring the course to life after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“Finally, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about it now, in my last year?’
According to her, no one had ever told her how important sleep was, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
This year’s course for the first time explained to the students how the basics of good sleep habits contribute to academic and sporting performance and also improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the university’s health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, students see the image of a room in a residence and click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes and books, where they receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the effects of sleep deprivation on sports performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, and cancer.
They are then encouraged to reflect on their daily routine using a map of the university site with interactive symbols.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know this – just as you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health,” added Professor Czeisler.
Pride in pushing a “night layer” is still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Ensuring good enough sleep should be the “secret weapon” of all students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and weight gain could be avoided because sleep deprivation puts the brain in hunger mode so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to conceive the course. He had taken one of his courses last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and encouraged him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step, all postgraduate students will be asked to complete a similar study program before taking up their studies at the competitive university.
According to the recommendation of Professor Czeisler, students should take a wake-up call for sleep time and wake-up time and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" that comes from electronic screens and LED lighting and can bring the circadian rhythm out of the clock.
