“The fact that a swift political decision in either Washington or Beijing could create the conditions for economic turmoil in both countries is actually much more dangerous than many observers have realized before,” says Abigail Grace, a research fellow at the Center for New American Security think tank in Asia.
Syria is “ready” for the return of refugees, says Foreign Minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country devastated by the seven-year war.
In a speech to the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that conditions in the country are improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and safer thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government is rebuilding the areas destroyed by terrorists in order to restore normality.
All conditions are now given for the voluntary return of refugees to the country, which they had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country are in need of humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian government welcomes help to rebuild the devastated country.
However, he stressed that it would not accept conditional assistance from countries that had supported the uprising.
Europe wins the Ryder Cup in Paris
Team Europa won the 2018 Ryder Cup and defeated Team USA with a finish score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National near Paris.
The United States has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe won back the crown after the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points it needed to defeat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who had problems over much of the tournament, sank his slack on the 16th track (Par 3) in the water and lost to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari was able to shine in all his rounds and became one of 4 players to score a 5-0-0 since the tournament began in its current format in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was defeated 5:4 by the player with the lowest ranking in Team Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
The world's best-ranked player, Dustin Johnson, lost 2-1 to England's Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
Spanish Sergio Garcia, a veteran of eight Ryder Cups, became the best European Ryder Cup player of all time with 25.5 career points.
“I usually don’t cry, but today I couldn’t hold back.
It was a difficult year.
I am so grateful that Thomas chose me and believed in me.
I’m so happy to win back the cup.
It’s about the team and I’m happy to have made a contribution,” said the emotional Garcia after the European victory.
He continues the torch to his compatriot John Rahm, who won against American golf legend Tiger Woods 2:1 in the singles on Sunday.
“I’m so incredibly proud to have beaten Tiger Woods that I’ve been watching on TV since I was a child,” Rahm said.
Woods lost all his four games in France and now has a Ryder Cup record of 13-21-3.
A strange statistic for one of the greatest players of all time, who has won 14 important titles and is only surpassed by Jack Nicklaus.
The U.S. team had trouble finding the fairways all weekend, except for Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who performed high-profile performances throughout the tournament.
U.S. captain Jim Furyk said after a disappointing performance of his team: “I’m proud of the guys, they’ve fought.
There was a time this morning when we had put pressure on Europe.
We didn't do anything about it.
Hats off to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All of his 12 players performed well.
We’ll regroup, I’ll talk to the PGA America and our Ryder Cup committee and we’ll look forward.
I love these 12 guys and I’m proud to be their captain.
You have to pull the hat.
We were defeated.”
Red tide update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota are decreasing
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, the areas of the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier are experiencing more opaque flowering conditions, indicating decreasing concentrations.
A red algae bloom extends over approximately 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the south of the district of Lee.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
A red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
In the past week, average concentrations in or off the coast of Pinellas County have been reported, low to high concentrations off the coast of Manatee County, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Charlotte County, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Collier County, Lee County, and low concentrations off the coast of Collier County.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No new respiratory problems have been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
